To make MonsterTools installable as a native VS Code extension, you need to bundle both the TypeScript frontend interface and your compiled C# engine binary into a single .vsix file.
VS Code extensions can carry self-contained native executables inside their installation folder. When a user installs the extension, your C# engine is deployed automatically alongside the UI. [1] 
Here is the exact step-by-step process to package, wire, and deploy it.
------------------------------
## Step 1: Update the Build Output Path
First, configure your C# project to output its production binary directly into your extension's workspace. This ensures the engine is always present when you build or bundle the extension.
Open your MonsterTools/MonsterTools.csproj file and add a custom release path that points directly into the monster-ui folder:

<PropertyGroup Condition="'$(Configuration)' == 'Release'">
    <OutputPath>../monster-ui/bin/</OutputPath>
    <AppendTargetFrameworkToOutputPath>false</AppendTargetFrameworkToOutputPath>
</PropertyGroup>

Run a production publish command to compile your engine as a self-contained executable for your target operating system (e.g., Windows):

dotnet publish MonsterTools.sln -c Release -r win-x64 --self-contained true

------------------------------
## Step 2: Configure the Runtime Path in the Extension
Now that the compiled C# app sits inside monster-ui/bin/MonsterTools.exe, update your monster-ui/src/extension.ts file to dynamically find the engine relative to where the extension is installed on the user's machine.
Update the binary path line in extension.ts to look like this:

// Locates the binary directly inside the installed extension folder frameworkconst engineBinary = path.join(context.extensionPath, 'bin', 'MonsterTools.exe');

------------------------------
## Step 3: Bundle the Extension using vsce [2] 
To bundle the files into an installable plugin, use @vscode/vsce (the official Visual Studio Code Extension Manager tool). [3] 

   1. Open your terminal and navigate directly into your monster-ui directory.
   2. Install the bundler tool globally:
   
   npm install -g @vscode/vsce
   
   3. Compile your TypeScript code into production-ready JavaScript:
   
   npm run compile
   
   4. Package the extension into a single file:
   
   vsce package
   
   [4, 5, 6, 7, 8] 

This command will output a file named monster-ui-1.0.0.vsix in your directory. This single archive contains your webview sidebar interface, your TypeScript bridge code, and your fully self-contained C# orchestration engine.
------------------------------
## Step 4: Installing it locally
Because you are running a completely custom local architecture bypassing the public marketplace, you can install your .vsix file manually into your main VS Code editor: [9] 

   1. Open VS Code.
   2. Open the Extensions tab (Ctrl+Shift+X or Cmd+Shift+X).
   3. Click the ... (Views and More Actions) menu in the top-right corner of the extensions sidebar.
   4. Select Install from VSIX...
   5. Select your newly generated monster-ui-1.0.0.vsix file. [10, 11, 12, 13, 14] 

The MonsterTools beaker icon will instantly appear in your primary Activity Bar. The moment you open any workspace folder, your TypeScript plugin will wake up, spawn your C# engine in the background, lock onto the directory, and prepare your deterministic local workers.
