## The Clean, Proxy-Free Architecture Pipeline
Without the Node.js proxy, your pipeline is direct, highly responsive, and keeps the data strictly within your own control loop:

[VS Code Layout View] ◄──(Local IPC / JSON-RPC via WebSockets)──► [MonsterTools Engine]
  │                                                                 │ (Orchestrates Loop)
  ▼ (User Prompt Entry)                                             ├─► Runs BuildWorker
                                                                    ├─► Runs FileWorkers
                                                                    └─► Interrogates LM Studio


   1. User Prompt Entry: The user types an instruction directly into your dedicated MonsterTools UI Sidebar in VS Code.
   2. Direct Forwarding: The thin VS Code extension reads the active workspace directory path and forwards the raw prompt text straight down to your native MonsterTools C# Core Engine using high-speed local WebSockets.
   3. Deterministic Orchestration: Your C# core (AgentLoop.cs and ToolRouter.cs) takes complete ownership of the request. It reads the file trees, executes compilers (BuildWorker.cs), and tracks the continuous state matrix.
   4. Isolated Inference Interrogation: When your C# loop needs a logic decision, it speaks directly to LM Studio via raw HTTP client calls (LMStudioService.cs). The LLM evaluates the concise reasoning packet and passes its raw structural choices back to the C# core.
   5. Real-Time UI Reflection: As the C# engine updates files or watches a build output, it pipes live JSON status logs back up the WebSocket channel, instantly updating the indicators inside your custom VS Code sidebar view.

------------------------------
## Why Removing the Proxy Makes Your Project Work Better

* Zero Schema Distortion: You no longer have to force-translate your deterministic worker payloads into standard OpenAI chat completion arrays. You can pass raw, highly optimized structured data directly between the UI and C# code.
* No More UI Timeouts: The standard GitHub Copilot extension will aggressively drop a connection if a local model takes too long to respond during a deep multi-step build loop. Your custom UI panel will hold an indefinite local connection, allowing your agent loops to run for as long as needed to fix an error.
* Tighter Project Integration: Your C# application can leverage deep workspace access without the Node.js layer scrambling the file path references or hitting access permission walls.

------------------------------
## Verifying the Absolute Minimum Requirements for the Extension
To fully package and install this as a unified .vsix plugin, your frontend extension directory (monster-ui/) only requires three simple code scripts to drive the entire presentation layer:

   1. package.json: Standard text manifest that places the custom sidebar beaker icon onto the primary VS Code sidebar panel.
   2. extension.ts: The thin activator script that locates your compiled MonsterTools.exe and launches it silently as a low-level background child process when VS Code boots.
   3. MonsterSidebarProvider.ts: The bridge script that creates the local loopback server to pipe real-time engine telemetry variables into the HTML panel view without processing any heavy business logic.

Your entire project becomes an elegant, high-performance local platform where the TypeScript extension handles visual presentation, the C# core handles system orchestration, and LM Studio acts strictly as an on-demand reasoning calculator.
